AdaptVisR: Bayesian Multitask Deep Learning for Multimorbidity Risk Prediction (R Implementation)
This R package provides the official implementation of the Bayesian Multitask Deep Learning (BMTDL) framework proposed in the paper:
Uncertainty-Aware Multimorbidity Risk Prediction via Bayesian Multitask Deep Learning
Ye Chen, Xiaoqun Qin, Shouping Chen
BMC Medical Informatics and Decision Making (Under Review)
The package is built with a full-stack adaptive learning system and supports multimodal data fusion, dynamic gated multitask learning, Bayesian uncertainty quantification, and causal discovery from wearable time-series data.
✨ Features
• ✅ Multimodal fusion of structured EHR, clinical text (via BioClinicalBERT embeddings), and wearable sensor data
• ✅ Dynamic gated multitask learning with GRU-based gates for time-varying inter-disease associations
• ✅ Bayesian uncertainty propagation using covariance priors and task-correlated Monte Carlo dropout
• ✅ Causal longitudinal modeling (CLSTM-BPR) for discovering dynamic causal pathways
• ✅ Comprehensive evaluation tools including ablation studies, sensitivity analysis, and clinical case visualizations
• ✅ R implementation with native S3/R6 classes, seamless integration with tidyverse and torch for R (via torch package)
📋 Requirements
• R >= 4.1.0
• Python environment with reticulate (for BioClinicalBERT and optional PyTorch backend) – if needed
• Key R packages:
◦ torch (for deep learning)
◦ dplyr, tidyr, ggplot2 (for data manipulation and visualization)
◦ reticulate (for interfacing with Python transformers)
◦ igraph, ggraph (for causal graph visualization)
◦ progressr (for progress bars)
Install dependencies from CRAN:
install.packages(c("torch", "dplyr", "tidyr", "ggplot2", "reticulate", "igraph", "ggraph", "progressr"))
🔧 Installation
You can install the development version of AdaptVisR from GitHub:
# install.packages("devtools")
devtools::install_github("CIAM-Lab/AdaptVisR")
🚀 Quick Start
1. Load the package
library(AdaptVisR)
2. Prepare data
Download NHANES data (2011–2018) from the CDC website. Use the built-in preprocessing function:
# Example: preprocess raw NHANES files
preprocessed_data <- preprocess_nhanes(
  data_dir = "path/to/nhanes/raw",
  outcome_years = 5,
  diseases = c("DM", "HTN", "CKD", "CHD", "Stroke")
)
3. Train the BMTDL model
model <- bmtdl(
  formula = ~ age + bmi + hba1c + ...,   # specify predictors
  data = preprocessed_data,
  task_names = c("DM", "HTN", "CKD", "CHD", "Stroke"),
  dynamic_gating = TRUE,
  bayesian = TRUE,
  causal_module = TRUE,
  mc_samples = 100,
  dropout_rate = 0.3,
  shrinkage_alpha = 0.9,
  epochs = 50,
  batch_size = 64,
  verbose = TRUE
)
4. Evaluate and visualize
# Predict on test set
predictions <- predict(model, newdata = test_data, type = "prob", interval = "confidence")

# Compute metrics
metrics <- evaluate(model, test_data)
print(metrics)

# Generate uncertainty analysis plots
plot_uncertainty(predictions, test_data$true_labels)

# Discover causal graphs from wearable data
causal_graph <- discover_causal_graph(model, patient_id = 123, wearable_data = wd)
plot(causal_graph)
📁 Package Structure
AdaptVisR/
├── R/                      # Core R functions
│   ├── fusion.R            # Cross-modal attention fusion
│   ├── gated_mtl.R         # Dynamic gated multitask learning
│   ├── bayesian.R          # Bayesian uncertainty (covariance prior + MC dropout)
│   ├── causal.R            # CLSTM-BPR causal discovery
│   ├── preprocessing.R     # NHANES data preprocessing
│   ├── evaluation.R        # Metrics and evaluation
│   └── visualization.R     # Plotting functions
├── man/                    # Documentation (generated by roxygen2)
├── inst/                   # Additional files (e.g., Docker, examples)
├── data/                   # Example datasets (if any)
├── DESCRIPTION             # Package metadata
├── NAMESPACE               # Exported functions
├── LICENSE                 # MIT License
├── README.md               # This file
└── cran-comments.md        # For CRAN submission (if applicable)
📈 Reproducing Paper Results
We provide vignettes and scripts to reproduce the key results from the paper. After installation, run:
# Reproduce Table 2 (main results)
vignette("table2_main_results")

# Reproduce Figure 2 (uncertainty analysis)
vignette("figure2_uncertainty")

# Reproduce ablation study (Table 4)
vignette("table4_ablation")
All vignettes are available in the package and can also be found in the vignettes/ directory of the repository.
🐳 Docker Support
A Docker image with all dependencies pre-installed is available for easy reproducibility:
docker pull ciamlab/adaptvisr:latest
docker run -it --rm ciamlab/adaptvisr R
The Dockerfile is located in docker/.
